title: San Francisco 49ers rookie Jarryd Hayne devastated by fumble against Baltimore Ravens

An evening to forget for Hayne Jarryd Hayne fumbles in one of two touches for the 49ers. San Francisco snapped a four game losing streak with a 5-point win over Baltimore.
PT1M25S 620 349 As it happened: 49ers v Ravens Andrew Johns drops by to watch Hayne Plane LOS ANGELES: Jarryd Hayne says he was devastated by his latest punt return fumble.
The Australian rugby league convert caught the ball in the first quarter on Sunday against the Baltimore Ravens and, with the help of his San Francisco 49ers' teammates blocking, beat four defenders.
Backfield in motion: Running back Jarryd Hayne lines up against the Baltimore Ravens. Photo: Getty Images
Hayne figured he'd just have the punter to beat to get a touchdown, but trailing behind him was the Ravens' Anthony Levine who knocked the ball out of his right hand.
Advertisement It was Hayne's third fumble in his six regular-season NFL games and he expects his coaches to drill him about it. "I was obviously devastated with the fumble," Hayne told reporters after the 49ers staved off the Ravens to score a 25-20 victory on Sunday on their home field, Levi's Stadium.
"We always talk about that - the most dangerous man is the man you don't see. I'm sure I'll be asked about that during the week."
That winning feeling: Jarryd Hayne walks off the field after the San Francisco 49ers beat the Baltimore Ravens at Levi's Stadium. Photo: Ezra Shaw
Hayne has just four days to prepare for the 49ers' next game when they host bitter rivals the Seattle Seahawks, who also have a two-win, four-loss record and are battling to stay in playoff contention.
The teams play in the same division, so the loser's playoff hopes will likely be snuffed out.
The 49ers, led by quarterback Colin Kaepernick passing for 340 yards, two touchdowns and no interceptions, were too strong for the Ravens. It was Hayne's worst NFL performance, with the 49ers electing to give the Australian the back-up running back duties to Carlos Hyde, who was hampered by a foot injury.
Hayne spent plenty of time on the field when Hyde rested, but never touched the ball. His inexperience showed when he failed to block two Baltimore Ravens from sacking Kaepernick. Hayne said he wasn't sure what happened on the play, but would review the tape before the Seahawks game.
"We'll have a look at it and nut it down," he said.
AAP
